---
import RoomLayout from '../../layouts/RoomLayout.astro';
---

<RoomLayout
  room="reading"
  title="Reading Room"
  subtitle="The library's books, papers, and primary sources."
  width="prose"
  sourceId="reading-toc"
>
  <section class="reading-room mt-8">
    <h2>Books</h2>

    <article class="reading-card">
      <div class="cover">
        <img
          src="/img/covers/schools-of-the-republic-cover.jpg"
          alt="Schools of the Republic cover"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'; this.parentElement.classList.add('plss-pattern')"
        />
      </div>
      <div class="meta">
        <span class="eyebrow">Booklet · Sullivan and Bird · 2025</span>
        <h2>Schools of the Republic</h2>
        <div class="byline">A Nine-Chapter Synthesis on America's School Trust Lands · Substrate v1.3</div>
        <p class="abstract">
          A nine-chapter synthesis of America's school trust lands — from the 1785 Land
          Ordinance to the present, with the constitutional architecture, the doublings of
          the antebellum and Reconstruction eras, the twentieth-century high-water mark, and
          the modern drift. The fifty per-state companion entries that originally formed Part
          II of the book are now distributed across this library's per-state dossiers —
          find your state in the Reading Room or on the Atlas.
        </p>
        <details class="toc">
          <summary>Table of contents</summary>
          <ol class="numbered-toc">
            <li><a href="/reading/prologue/">Prologue</a></li>
            <li><a href="/reading/founding-floor/">The Founding Floor — 1785, the Land Ordinance, and the school clause</a></li>
            <li><a href="/reading/statehood-without-federal-floor/">Statehood Without a Federal Floor — the Original 13 and the eastern path</a></li>
            <li><a href="/reading/northwest-ordinance-template/">The Northwest Ordinance Template — Section 16 enters the federal-grant statehood compact</a></li>
            <li><a href="/reading/antebellum-doubling/">Antebellum Doubling — California, Oregon, and the doubled grant</a></li>
            <li><a href="/reading/reconstruction-western-stack/">The Reconstruction Western Stack — the post-1867 admissions and the railroad-era pressures</a></li>
            <li><a href="/reading/twentieth-century-high-water-mark/">The Twentieth-Century High-Water Mark — fund growth and stewardship intervals</a></li>
            <li><a href="/reading/comparative-atlas/">Comparative Atlas — what fifty states reveal at a glance</a></li>
            <li><a href="/reading/conclusion/">Conclusion — what the trusts ask of us now</a></li>
          </ol>
        </details>
        <a href="/reading/schools-of-the-republic/" class="cta">Read the booklet</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="reading-card">
      <div class="cover">
        <img
          src="/img/covers/sacred-compact-cover.jpg"
          alt="Sacred Compact cover"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'; this.parentElement.classList.add('plss-pattern')"
        />
      </div>
      <div class="meta">
        <span class="eyebrow">White paper · 70 pages</span>
        <h2>The Sacred Compact</h2>
        <div class="byline">
          Dave Sullivan and Margaret Bird · v5.0 (May 2026) · 207 footnotes
        </div>
        <p class="abstract">
          A fiduciary-architecture analysis of America's school trust lands and funds. The
          1785 land ordinance as the assumed floor; the trust as covenant; the drift from
          compact to commodity; calling the state to account, both individual and
          institutional.
        </p>
        <details class="toc">
          <summary>Annotated table of contents</summary>
          <ol>
            <li>The compact, 1785–1789.</li>
            <li>The trust mechanism: corpus, beneficiary, fiduciary.</li>
            <li>Admission-era doublings and the school clause.</li>
            <li>The drift — what fiduciary breach looks like in practice.</li>
            <li>State accountability: individual and institutional.</li>
            <li>Recovery: the path forward through litigation, transparency, and reform.</li>
            <li>Anchor: a forever gift to forever schools for a forever democracy.</li>
            <li>Conclusion: the public ledger of America's school trusts.</li>
          </ol>
        </details>
        <a href="/reading/sacred-compact-prologue/" class="cta">Read the paper</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <h2>Bibliography</h2>
    <p class="kicker">Foundational works for understanding America's school trusts.</p>

    <article class="reading-card">
      <div class="cover">
        <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="meta">
        <span class="eyebrow">Foundational · 1911</span>
        <h2>History of Public Permanent Common School Funds in the United States, 1795–1905</h2>
        <div class="byline">Fletcher Harper Swift · Columbia University · 1911</div>
        <p class="abstract">
          The seminal academic study of America's school trust funds. Comprehensive
          state-by-state accounting of permanent common school funds from inception through
          1905. Public domain. The standard reference; no comprehensive successor work has
          been published since. Local PDF and source page now live.
        </p>
        <details class="toc">
          <summary>Read the source</summary>
          <p>
            Source page at
            <a href="/reading/sources/swift-1911/">/reading/sources/swift-1911/</a>;
            local PDF at
            <a href="/sources/historyofpublicp00swif.pdf">/sources/historyofpublicp00swif.pdf</a> (30&nbsp;MB).
            Original digitization on
            <a href="https://archive.org/details/historyofpublicp00swif" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Internet Archive</a>.
          </p>
        </details>
        <a href="/reading/sources/swift-1911/" class="cta">Read the source page</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="reading-card">
      <div class="cover">
        <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="meta">
        <span class="eyebrow">Foundational · 1949</span>
        <h2>A History of the Irreducible School Fund in Oregon</h2>
        <div class="byline">Norman B. Hawk · University of Oregon · June 1949 (digitized 2018)</div>
        <p class="abstract">
          Norman B. Hawk's 1949 University of Oregon doctoral thesis on the Oregon
          Irreducible School Fund. Foundational reference for the project's Oregon-specific
          case material. PDF and source page now live; full bibliographic confirmation
          pending.
        </p>
        <details class="toc">
          <summary>Read the source</summary>
          <p>
            Source page at
            <a href="/reading/sources/hawk-2018/">/reading/sources/hawk-2018/</a>;
            local PDF at
            <a href="/sources/hawk_09072018_final.pdf">/sources/hawk_09072018_final.pdf</a> (89&nbsp;MB).
          </p>
        </details>
        <a href="/reading/sources/hawk-2018/" class="cta">Read the source page</a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="reading-card">
      <div class="cover">
        <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="meta">
        <span class="eyebrow">Investigative · 1908</span>
        <h2>Looters of the Public Domain</h2>
        <div class="byline">S.A.D. Puter and Horace Stevens · 1908</div>
        <p class="abstract">
          Contemporaneous account of the Oregon land-fraud trials of the early 1900s.
          Primary-source material on the Mitchell trial and the broader pattern of
          public-land grift in the West. Public domain. Available on Internet Archive.
        </p>
        <details class="toc">
          <summary>External source</summary>
          <p>
            Full text on
            <a
              href="https://archive.org/details/lootersofpublicd00puteuoft"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener"
              >Internet Archive</a
            >.
          </p>
        </details>
        <a
          href="https://archive.org/details/lootersofpublicd00puteuoft"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="cta">Read on Internet Archive →</a
        >
      </div>
    </article>

    <article class="reading-card">
      <div class="cover">
        <div class="plss-pattern"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="meta">
        <span class="eyebrow">Academic · 2014</span>
        <h2>Closing the Book on the School Trust Lands</h2>
        <div class="byline">Heidelberg · National Agricultural Law Center · 2014</div>
        <p class="abstract">
          Recent academic analysis of state-level school trust lands accounting and reform
          pathways. Cites Swift 1911 as the seminal reference and updates with 21st-century
          data.
        </p>
        <details class="toc">
          <summary>External source</summary>
          <p>
            <a
              href="https://nationalaglawcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/assets/bibarticles/heidelberg_trust.pdf"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener"
              >National Agricultural Law Center</a
            >.
          </p>
        </details>
        <a
          href="https://nationalaglawcenter.org/wp-content/uploads/assets/bibarticles/heidelberg_trust.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="cta">Read the paper →</a
        >
      </div>
    </article>

    <p class="kicker" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
      More titles being added in upcoming months. If you know of a book or paper that
      belongs in this bibliography, suggest it via
      <a href="https://github.com/dave-schooltrustlands/schooltrustlands-encyclopedia/issues"
        >GitHub issues</a
      >.
    </p>
  </section>
</RoomLayout>
